Citation.sAbstract: Apparent molar volumes V2,f, apparent molar isentropic compressibilities KS,2,f and  viscosity B-coefficients have been determined for L-ascorbic acid, nicotinic acid, thiamine  hydrochloride and pyridoxine hydrochloride in water at temperatures (288.15 to 318.15) K from  density, sound velocity and viscosity measurements, respectively. Partial molar volumes V2o and  partial molar isentropic compressibilities KoS,2 at infinite dilution, and viscosity B-coefficients have  been calculated from the corresponding data. The partial molar expansibilities VEo (VEo = ( YV2o/   YT)P), second order derivative ( Y2V2o/  YT2)P, relative association (RA), specific acoustic impedance  (Z) and solvation number (Sn) have been calculated. Both volumetric and viscometric studies indicate  that nicotinic acid acts as structure promoter where as other vitamins act as structure destroyer. The  transition state theory has been used to calculate the activation free energy for viscous flow.
Citation.sTitle: Volumetric and viscometric studies on L-ascorbic acid, nicotinic acid, thiamine hydrochloride and  pyridoxine hydrochloride in water at temperatures (288.15 to 318.15) K and at atmospheric pressure
sKeyword: Volumetric and viscometric properties, L-ascorbic acid, nicotinic acid, thiamine
